			<section id="promoter-apply">
				<div class="well well-large">
					<header><h3 class="lead">So Who Organizes the Show?</h3></header>
					<div class="row-fluid">
						<div class="span2">
							<ul class="nav nav-list">
			          <li class="nav-header">How it Works</li>
			          <li class="divider"></li>
			          <li class=""><a href="#">Organizing >></a></li>
			          <li class=""><a href="#">Funding >></a></li>
			          <li class=""><a href="#">Touring  >></a></li>
			          <li class=""><a href="#">Supporting >></a></li>
			          <li class=""><a href="#">Attending >></a></li>
			          <li class=""><a href="#">Payment >></a></li>
			          <li class="divider"></li>
			        </ul>
			        <div class="btn-group center">
								<a href="#invite" class="btn btn-block btn-large btn-primary" data-toggle="modal">Request Invite</a>
							</div>
						</div>
						<div class="span10">
							<blockquote>
								<p><strong>Initially at least</strong> my idea is to vet prospective promoters as opposed to having a completely open community, although there is technically no reason to prevent the latter. There could be a fee for membership dependent on the level of promoter activity.</p><br>
								<p>Ordinary users can choose to create an account with 100 Motels when purchasing tickets but for promoters there's a different process. </p>
							  <p>If you click the signup button below you will be taken to Stripe.com to either authorize an existing account for use with 100 Motels or to create one.
									This enables promoters to be paid directly and is only available to US or Canadian citizens at the time of writing.</p>
								<p>100 Motels recieves a per transaction fee for each ticket purchased while Stripe's processing fees are applied directly to the promoter's account.</p> <br>
								<p>For more details on this and all other technical queries regarding the service click on the 'More Info' button below.</p>
							</blockquote>
